HEADWORD: Tutelage
<hw>Tu"te*lage</hw> <pr>(t⟦umac⟧"t⟦esl⟧*l⟦asl⟧j; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>tutela</ets> protection, fr. <ets>tutus</ets> safe, fr.
<ets>tueri</ets> to watch, defend. Cf. <er>Tuition</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of guarding or protecting; guardianship;
protection; <as>as, the king's right of seigniory and
<ex>tutelage</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The childhood of the European nations was passed under the
<qex>tutelage</qex> of the clergy.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being under a guardian; care or
protection enjoyed.</def> <rj><au>V. Knox.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tutelary</ent>⟦br⟧
